Introduction¶

In this assignment, we are to explore customer departures from a business, based on customers' given attributes.

In the competitive telecommunications industry, customer churn is a significant concern as retaining customers is often more cost-effective than acquiring new ones. Churn happens when customers discontinue their services. The most prominent factors that influence this decision are quality, pricing, customer support, and the availablility of alternative services.

Our aim is to enable companies to pinpoint potential churners using available data.

Variable Description:
cust_id: Unique identifier for each customer.
region: Geographical region where the customer is located.
tenure: Number of months the customer has been with the company.
age: Age of customer
marital: Marital status of the customer.
address: Address of customer
income: Yearly income (in thousands)
ed: Education level
employ: Number of years customer has been employed.
retire: Retirement status
gender: Gender of the customer.
reside: Length of time at current address.
tollfree: Whether customer has toll-free number.
equip: Whether customer has equipment.
callcard: Whether customer has calling card.
wireless: Whether the customer has wireless service.
longmon: Monthly long-distance call usage.
tollmon: Monthly toll-free call usage.
equipmon: Monthly equipment usage.
cardmon: Monthly call card usage.
wiremon: Monthly wireless usage.
longten: Long distance call tenure total.
tollten: Toll-free call tenure total.
equipten: Equipement usage total tenure.
cardten: Calling card usage total tenure.
wireten: Wireless usage total tenure.
multline: Whether customer has multiple lines.
voice: Whether customer uses voice services.
pager: Whether customer uses pager services.
internet: Whether customer uses internet services.
callid: Whether customer uses caller id.
callwait: Whether customer uses call waiting.
forward: Whether customer uses call forwarding.
confer: Whether customer uses conference calls.
ebill: Whether customer uses electronic billing.
loglong: Logarithmic transformation of long-distance call usage.
lninc: Logarithmic transformation of income.
custcat: Customer category.
churn: Target variable representing churn.

Data Understanding and Preprocessing¶

During this section I examined the dataset for any missing values, ensuring data completeness and integrity. I transformed all categorical variables stored as 'object' data types into 'category' types. I created a variety of visualizations to explore the relationships between churn and key variables.

Model Development¶

In model developement, the primary goal is to prepare the dataset for building a predictive model to identify customer churn.

I used get_dummies to transform the categorial variables into binary features. I ran into a lot of trouble initially because I forgot to remove cust_id and address.

I partitioned the data into a training set and a testing set. 70% was allocated as training data and 30% as testing data. I also ran into a lot of problems while creating the decision tree because the churn data was N/Y instead of 0/1. This issue didn't really come up during lab03 but nevertheless I opted to map the labels from n/y to 0/1. (this map code I got on the internet).

With the above we can see that our data is clearly unbalanced. with ~75% of No churn and ~25% Yes churn. Balancing the data is not necessary with this assignment but it asks how I would do it if it was. The following is the process to balance the data:

Combine predictors_train and target_train into a single DataFrame:
combined_train_df = pd.concat([predictors_train, target_train], axis=1)

Separate majority and minority classes:
majority_df = combined_train_df[combined_train_df['churn'] == 'No']
minority_df = combined_train_df[combined_train_df['churn'] == 'Yes']

Undersample the majority class randomly:
undersampled_majority = majority_df.sample(n=len(minority_df), random_state=5)

Combine the undersampled majority class and the minority class:
undersampled_data = pd.concat([undersampled_majority, minority_df])

Shuffle the combined DataFrame to ensure randomness:
balanced_data = undersampled_data.sample(frac=1, random_state=5)

Split the balanced_data into predictors_train and target_train:
predictors_train = balanced_data.drop(columns=['churn'])
target_train = balanced_data['churn']

Results and Model Evaluation¶

The overall accuracy of the model is 87%, as seen with the results/classification report below. This is generally a good score and the aim was for it to be between 70-80%, but we must dig deeper to see if this model is worthy.

Starting with class 0 (no churn), 89% of the customers predicted were actually correct, and 92% of the customers who actually did not churn were correctly identified (recall). This gives us a 0.91 (91%) f1-score which is very good.

Now moving on to class 1 (churn), 80% of the customers predicted as "churn" were correct, and 72% of the actual churners were correctly identified. This gives us a f1-score of 0.76 which is not so good.

The whole basis of this model was to identify churners, and with a recall of 72%, this means that 28% of actual churners were missed!

Conclusion¶

In this project, I was tasked to employ a decision tree classifier to predict customer churn within a telecommunications company. I began with researching what factors contribute to customer churn within the telecommunications industy. After preprocessing the data, I started to develop the decision tree model by partitioning the data into training and test sets. I used a maximum depth of 10.

The model achieved an overall accuracy of 87%, which indicates it performs quite well. However, after analyzing deeper, the model's performance in identifiying churners was lacking. While the precision for churners was 80%, the recall was only 72%, meaing 28% of the actual churners were not identified by the model! This can have serious implications for businesses relying on the model to retain at-risk customers, since missed churners could leave without any retention effort.

Strengths of my approach would include:

  • The model's overall performance, especially identfiying non-churners. (for promotions, etc)
  • The accuracy and precision for classifying customers as non-churners, which show the model can be trusted for a large portion of the customer base.

Weaknesses in my approach would include:

  • The recall for churners is not as high as desired. The model missed 28% of actual churners, which limits its effectiveness for businesses.
  • No balancing was used during this project which might have made the model much better.

While the model provides a foundation for predicting customer churn, I think businessess should be cautious when relying solely on this classifier. It's current strengths lie with identifying non-churners accurately, which is not the intended use of the model. The model was made to capture all at-risk customers, and it fails to do so 28% of the time.
